DisplayName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
AlertName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
Description:
Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

DisplayName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
AlertName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
Description:
A known credential theft tool execution command line was detected.
Either the process itself or its command line indicated an intent to dump users' credentials, keys, plain-text passwords and more.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]
ExtendedProperties:
{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"CredentialAccess","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:01:45","IncidentId":"321","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert, collect artifacts, and determine scope 
1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"f5d3c5d8-ec3a-4412-ab45-934d8faff42c","MitreTechniques":"T1003","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

Description: In order to obtain clear-text password, attackers must decrypt the user's password from the LSASS service's memory. Multiple public tools as well as custom ones could be used to perform this operation. Once obtained, these credentials are often used in lateral movement activities to infiltrate other machines and servers in the network.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

Description:
The Mimikatz hacktool was detected on this device. Mimikatz is a credential theft tool that can harvest plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets.  An attacker might be trying to harvest credentials to log into this or other devices on the network, by impersonating a valid user.

For more information, read the Mimikatz tool profile Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/51db19ab-081f-46f3-9fe1-3f5e5d2f8ee0/analystreport? and read the Actor profile: Storm-0875 Threat Analytics report https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/4f60801d-912e-4bcb-91b2-f46879c8a718/analystreport

Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

Because this malware was active, take precautionary measures and check for residual signs of infection.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that is related to the alert. Inspect parent processes and why they were launched.
2. Take note of the name of the remote device and the command that might have been executed.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.​
5. Check the timeline of both the devices for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident.
1. Find related alerts and activities on both devices. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph.
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors.
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords
4. Block IP addresses and URLs.
5. Install security updates.

D. DisplayName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
AlertName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
Description:
Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

Description:
System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssadmin.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssadmin.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbadmin.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbadmin.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]

DisplayName: Command and Control behavior was blocked
AlertName: Command and Control behavior was blocked
Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

Because this malware was active, take precautionary measures and check for residual signs of infection.

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"CommandAndControl","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:12:57","IncidentId":"323","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAv","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert and scope the suspected breach.
1. Find related machines, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.
2. Check for other suspicious activities in the machine timeline.
3. Locate unfamiliar processes in the process tree. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. 
5. Identify unusual system activity with system owners. 

B. If you have validated the alert, contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Record relevant artifacts, including those you need in mitigation rules.
2. Stop suspicious processes. Block prevalent malware files across the network.
3. Isolate affected machines.
4. Identify potentially compromised accounts. If necessary, reset passwords and decommission accounts.
5. Block relevant emails, websites, and IP addresses. Remove attack emails from mailboxes.
6. Update antimalware signatures and run full scans.

DisplayName: Unknown malware was detected and was active

Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

This detection might indicate that Windows Defender has stopped the malware from delivering its payload. However, it is prudent to check the machine for signs of infection.

DisplayName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
AlertName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
Description:
Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

Description:
System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssadmin.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssadmin.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbadmin.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbadmin.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]

Description:
The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware campaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport

DisplayName: Command and Control behavior was blocked
AlertName: Command and Control behavior was blocked
Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

Because this malware was active, take precautionary measures and check for residual signs of infection.

Description:
The actor that Microsoft tracks as Manatee Tempest is a Russia-based cybercriminal group that has been active since June 2014. It was notorious for one of its earliest malware campaigns – the Dridex banking trojan. Manatee Tempest is also one of the first groups to be sanctioned by the Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) in 2019.

Manatee Tempest’s tactics rely on a partnership with Mustard Tempest, an access broker that facilitates access to target networks. Manatee Tempest has been observed targeting organizations across a diverse array of industries with methods such as drive-by download, including malvertising and FakeUpdates (also known as SocGholish) infections facilitated by Mustard Tempest to obtain initial access, followed by BLISTER loader to deliver Cobalt Strike beacons which are used for lateral movement and ransomware deployment. The actor also uses domain fronting to establish command-and-control channel for Cobalt Strike beacons. Manatee Tempest overlaps with activity tracked by the cyber intelligence industry as EvilCorp, UNC2165, and Indrik Spider.

For more information, read the Actor Profile: Manatee Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/a22c3410-db8f-4c58-866e-ebb760e509d0/analystreport

Description:
System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssadmin.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssadmin.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbadmin.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbadmin.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]

•	Check if files on the affected device were encrypted by ransomware. If files were encrypted, isolate the affected devices.
•	Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities.
•	Check other devices on the network for the observed deleted file name, or SHA1.
•	Find the infection source and block it (IP or email).
•	Rebuild the affected device. 
•	Ensure your software has the latest patch, update your malware signatures, and close the vectors of attack.
•	Move out-of-date applications to other systems to reduce the attack surface.
•	Deploy the Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit (EMET) utility for behavioral-based exploit prevention.

Description:
System recovery setting tampering has been observed on this device. Adversaries might be attempting to delete or remove built-in operating system data and turn off recovery services to prevent recovering a corrupted system. This may deny access to available backups and recovery options.

Operating systems may contain features that can help fix corrupted systems, such as a backup catalog, volume shadow copies, and automatic repair features. Adversaries may stop or delete system recovery features to augment the effects of Data Destruction and Data Encrypted for Impact.

Many native Windows utilities have been used by adversaries to disable or delete system recovery features:
•	 vssadmin.exe can be used to delete all volume shadow copies on a system using the following command: [vssadmin.exe delete shadows /all /quiet]
•	Windows Management Instrumentation can be used to delete volume shadow copies using the following command: [wmic shadowcopy delete]
•	wbadmin.exe can be used to delete the Windows Backup Catalog using the following command: [wbadmin.exe delete catalog -quiet]
•	bcdedit.exe can be used to disable automatic Windows recovery features by modifying boot configuration data using the following command: [bcdedit.exe /set default bootstatuspolicy ignoreallfailures & bcdedit /set default recoveryenabled no]

DisplayName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
AlertName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
Description:
Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

DisplayName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
AlertName: Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT)
Description:
Possible attempt to access Primary Refresh Token (PRT) has been detected. A Primary Refresh Token (PRT) is a key artifact of Azure AD authentication on Windows 10, Windows Server 2016 and later versions, iOS, and Android devices. It is a JSON Web Token (JWT) that's specially issued to Microsoft first party token brokers to enable single sign-on (SSO) across the applications used on those devices. Attackers can attempt to access this resource to move laterally into organization or perform credential theft.

For more information, read the Activity profile: Midnight Blizzard credential attacks Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/e4aad043-a273-4f88-b65e-fdfc3996ec92/analystreport?

Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. {"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":"28","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":null,"LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:38:35","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to launch the command.
2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account or device and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised assets.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
6. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that the alert is a false positive:
     2.1 A user may have been suspended automatically. Revert the action by enabling the user account through the MDI portal or Active Directory.
     2.2 Devices may have been automatically contained. Revert the action through the device page in the portal.

D. Contact your incident response team or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"a438e864-e77a-43d1-8858-520e652f7c3d","MitreTechniques":"T1486","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

Because this malware was active, take precautionary measures and check for residual signs of infection.

AlertName: Possible compromised user account delivering ransomware-related files
Description: A user account was observed dropping a ransomware-related file on several devices. An attacker may have compromised the said user account to move laterally across the network and infect as many devices with ransomware as possible. Automated remediation action may be taken to disable the account.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]
ExtendedProperties:
{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Ransomware","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":"27","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":null,"LastUpdated":"06/20/2024 09:39:15","IncidentId":"107","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"Defender Experts","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to launch the command.
2. Look for recent signs of activity by the compromised user account and investigate them. Make sure to check other devices in your organization, as well as the original device associated with the compromised account.
3. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that may have occurred around the time of the alert.
4. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
5. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
6. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.

B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that you have a false positive, and a user has been suspended automatically, re-enable them via the MDI portal or Active Directory.

D. Contact your incident response team, or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"66879eb2-9072-4b56-bb9d-30919f78bdc5","MitreTechniques":"T1021;T1486;T1570","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

DisplayName: Lateral movement using SMB remote file access blocked on multiple devices
AlertName: Lateral movement using SMB remote file access blocked on multiple devices
Description: A contained user’s attempt to create, delete, or modify files over server message block (SMB) protocol was automatically blocked by attack disruption. An attacker might be trying to gain access to your organization, move laterally within your network, or remotely encrypt files.
RemediationSteps:
["A. Validate the alert.
1. Inspect the users that were compromised and any unfamiliar processes or applications that might have caused credential access.
2. Inspect the lateral movement path to ensure domain takeover does not occur.
3. Check for other suspicious activities in the timeline.

B. Scope the incident. Find related accounts and devices in the incident graph.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords. Quarantine affected devices to prevent lateral movement.

D. Contact your incident response team or contact Microsoft support for investigation and remediation services."]

DisplayName: Malicious Url detected in Proxy logs
AlertName: Malicious Url detected in Proxy logs
Description: Connection from 10.60.0.63 - vnevado-jump to vectorsandarrows.com has been seen on the proxy, please check on the computer what happened
ExtendedProperties:
{"Query Period":"14.00:00:00","Trigger Operator":"GreaterThan","Trigger Threshold":"0","Correlation Id":"691dc67f-ff1a-4de0-8330-690b74dcd3db","Search Query Results Overall Count":"2","Data Sources":"["cybersoc"]","Query":"// The query_now parameter represents the time (in UTC) at which the scheduled analytics rule ran to produce this alert.
set query_now = datetime(2024-06-20T10:12:14.9194220Z);
SquidProxy
| where TimeGenerated > ago(3h)
| extend Domain = tostring(iif(Url startswith "http", trim_end("/",tostring(split(Url, "//")[1])), split(Url, ':')[0]))
| project-rename ProxyUrl = Url
| join (ThreatIntelligenceIndicator 
    | where isnotempty(Url) and TimeGenerated > ago(14d)
    | extend Url_details = parse_url(Url)

DisplayName: Unexpected behavior observed by a process ran with no command line arguments
AlertName: Unexpected behavior observed by a process ran with no command line arguments
Description:
The legitimate process by this name does not normally exhibit this behavior when ran with no command line arguments. 
Such unexpected behavior may be a result of extraneous code injected into a legitimate process, or a malicious executable masquerading as the legitimate one by name.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"DefenseEvasion","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/26/2024 15:53:51","IncidentId":"350","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert, collect artifacts, and determine scope 
1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Execution","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/26/2024 12:03:44","IncidentId":"347","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"u141@ash.alpineskihouse.co","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that invoked the Powershell command. Inspect parent processes and the context of their execution.
2. Examine the PowerShell command to understand what commands were executed. Note: Content may need to be decoded if it is Base64-encoded. If enabled, pull PowerShell Operational Logs from the device to get additional details on the execution.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.​
5. Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident. 
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph. 
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. 
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. 
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords.
4. Block IP addresses and URLs.
5. Install security updates.​

D. DisplayName: An anomalous scheduled task was created
AlertName: An anomalous scheduled task was created
Description:
An anomalous scheduled task was created. This may be used by an attacker to obtain persistence on the device.

For further information on this threat, read the following threat analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/c9709a39-ac8d-493d-9a63-71da3ca1e745/analystreport
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"fae212ef-978a-40d3-9c1a-e17cebdeab72","MitreTechniques":"T1053","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

DisplayName: Suspicious PowerShell download or encoded command execution
AlertName: Suspicious PowerShell download or encoded command execution
Description: A process executed PowerShell to download a file or run an encoded command. PowerShell is often used by attackers to bypass security protection mechanisms by executing their payload in memory without leaving a trace or touching the disk. An attacker might be trying to download external payloads or execute commands in the device.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Execution","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/26/2024 12:03:35","IncidentId":"347","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"u141@ash.alpineskihouse.co","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that invoked the Powershell command. Inspect parent processes and the context of their execution.
2. Examine the PowerShell command to understand what commands were executed. Note: Content may need to be decoded if it is Base64-encoded. If enabled, pull PowerShell Operational Logs from the device to get additional details on the execution.
3. Identify downloaded file or content.
4. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
5. Check files for prevalence, reputation, their locations, and digital signatures.​
6. Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert, including the processes access the startup folder.
7. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident. 
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph. 
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, reputation, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. 
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. 
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Remove related files.
4. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords.
5. Block IP addresses and URLs.
6. Install security updates.​

D. Description:
A suspect LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) query was executed, indicating potential reconnaissance activity. 

LDAP queries are often used by attackers in attempt to learn the organization's structure, by querying the domain controller for administrative users and groups and interesting assets. 
Using this information, an attacker can gain higher privileges and access important assets in the organization.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

DisplayName: Suspicious PowerShell download or encoded command execution
AlertName: Suspicious PowerShell download or encoded command execution
Description: A process executed PowerShell to download a file or run an encoded command. PowerShell is often used by attackers to bypass security protection mechanisms by executing their payload in memory without leaving a trace or touching the disk. An attacker might be trying to download external payloads or execute commands in the device.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Execution","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/26/2024 12:03:35","IncidentId":"347","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":"u141@ash.alpineskihouse.co","Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that invoked the Powershell command. Inspect parent processes and the context of their execution.
2. Examine the PowerShell command to understand what commands were executed. Note: Content may need to be decoded if it is Base64-encoded. If enabled, pull PowerShell Operational Logs from the device to get additional details on the execution.
3. Identify downloaded file or content.
4. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
5. Check files for prevalence, reputation, their locations, and digital signatures.​
6. Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert, including the processes access the startup folder.
7. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident. 
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph. 
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, reputation, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. 
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. 
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Remove related files.
4. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords.
5. Block IP addresses and URLs.
6. Install security updates.​

D. 1. Inspect the process initiated the registry write for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal? 
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation 
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords.
6. Remove the suspicious registry entry
7. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"82aab9b3-8432-4708-a52f-1c05acb09f08","MitreTechniques":"T1112;T1547.001","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

DisplayName: An uncommon file was created and added to a Run Key
AlertName: An uncommon file was created and added to a Run Key
Description:
An uncommon file was observed being created on this machine, and was then put into a Registry Key where it will be run after a reboot. An attacker may place a malicious piece of software in such a location to prevent losing access if a machine is turned off.

For more information, read the Simulated threat Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/3d82501e-8ac3-4272-9ddc-59526ee32c4d/analystreport
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

DisplayName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
AlertName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
Description:
A known credential theft tool execution command line was detected.
Either the process itself or its command line indicated an intent to dump users' credentials, keys, plain-text passwords and more.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]
ExtendedProperties:
{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"CredentialAccess","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/27/2024 14:37:22","IncidentId":"357","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert, collect artifacts, and determine scope 
1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"f5d3c5d8-ec3a-4412-ab45-934d8faff42c","MitreTechniques":"T1003","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

2. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that might have occurred around the time of the alert.

2. If you believe that you have a false positive, and a user has been suspended automatically, re-enable them via the MDI portal or Active Directory.
D. {"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"Persistence","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/27/2024 14:37:22","IncidentId":"357","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"A. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that is related to the alert. Inspect parent processes and the context of their execution.
2. Note the new user account that was added.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.​
5. Check the device timeline for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident. 
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph. 
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. 
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach. 
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission or reset passwords of the compromised or added accounts.
4. Block IP addresses and URLs. 
5. Install security updates.

D. ExtendedProperties:
{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"LateralMovement","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":"36","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"PendingResource","LastUpdated":"06/27/2024 14:37:22","IncidentId":"357","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert
1. Examine the dropped files - Are you familiar with these files? Do they seem suspicious?
2. Look for any related alerts or suspicious activities on the device around or after the time of this alert. Find whether this alert is part of a wider incident containing additional related alerts and activities. The incident might already have correlated alerts, activities, and additional potentially impacted devices and other assets. Use the incident page as guide for the rest of the investigation.

Investigate threat scope and impact
1. Check whether any of the files were executed, and if so, assess the impact.
2. Identify the source of the dropped file. Determine whether the communication source is internal or external to the organization, and whether the activity is expected (for example, penetration testing).
3. Investigate the source and target devices for additional related alerts and activities. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident. The incident might already have correlated activities and impacted assets. Use the incident page as guide for the rest of your investigation. Use the alert page and device timelines to investigate related activities.
4. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. Identify communications to suspect network addresses & domains. Verify unusual activities with server owners.
5.  Pivot on any evidence entities to determine the full scope of the threat and find any additional impacted devices and other assets. Use the entity page Observed in org tab or Advanced Hunting to search for other occurrences of these indicators across the organization.

Contain the threat
1. If the activity on this device is unexpected and the device displays indications of compromise, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing. Assess productivity implications and potential attack risk before doing so.
2. If an internal source device was identified, isolate the source device. Assess the productivity implications and potential attack risk before doing so. If the source device identified is external, block communications to its network (IP) address.

Remediate the threat

DisplayName: Sign-in attempt with deceptive user account
AlertName: Sign-in attempt with deceptive user account
Description: A sign-in attempt was detected using a deceptive user account. A potential attacker might be using a fake or decoy user account on this device. Attackers might use the account to perform various attack activities, including lateral movement and accessing sensitive data.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

Validate the alert.
1. Check if the device owner or IT personnel had a legitimate reason to use the decoy account. If the decoy account was used legitimately, consider modifying the decoy name in the deception rule.
2. Review device timelines for suspicious activity that might have occurred around the time of the alert.
3. Look for unfamiliar processes. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors.
5. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other devices. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised devices.
B. Scope the incident. Find related devices, network addresses, and files in the incident graph.
C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. Stop suspicious processes, isolate affected systems, decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords, block IP addresses and URLs, and install security updates.
2. If you believe that you have a false positive, and a user has been suspended automatically, re-enable them via the MDI portal or Active Directory.
D. Multiple known public tools, which could also be used for malicious reasons were dropped on this device.
Attackers might download or copy multiple dual-purpose tools to the target device to perform various attack stages including, credential theft, privilege escalation, and lateral movement.

Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. 1. Examine the dropped files - Are you familiar with these files? Do they seem suspicious?
2. Look for any related alerts or suspicious activities on the device around or after the time of this alert. Find whether this alert is part of a wider incident containing additional related alerts and activities. The incident might already have correlated alerts, activities, and additional potentially impacted devices and other assets. Use the incident page as guide for the rest of the investigation.

Investigate threat scope and impact
1. Check whether any of the files were executed, and if so, assess the impact.
2. Identify the source of the dropped file. Determine whether the communication source is internal or external to the organization, and whether the activity is expected (for example, penetration testing).
3. Investigate the source and target devices for additional related alerts and activities. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident. The incident might already have correlated activities and impacted assets. Use the incident page as guide for the rest of your investigation. Use the alert page and device timelines to investigate related activities.
4. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors. Identify communications to suspect network addresses & domains. Verify unusual activities with server owners.
5.  Pivot on any evidence entities to determine the full scope of the threat and find any additional impacted devices and other assets. Use the entity page Observed in org tab or Advanced Hunting to search for other occurrences of these indicators across the organization.

Contain the threat
1. If the activity on this device is unexpected and the device displays indications of compromise, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing. Assess productivity implications and potential attack risk before doing so.
2. If an internal source device was identified, isolate the source device. Assess the productivity implications and potential attack risk before doing so. If the source device identified is external, block communications to its network (IP) address.

Remediate the threat
1. Clean up or reinstall affected devices to remove malicious components and return them to a clean state. Reset passwords of affected accounts. Add all identified threat indicators to block lists using the Indicators page.
2. DisplayName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
AlertName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
Description:
A known credential theft tool execution command line was detected.
Either the process itself or its command line indicated an intent to dump users' credentials, keys, plain-text passwords and more.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"CredentialAccess","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/27/2024 14:37:22","IncidentId":"357","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert, collect artifacts, and determine scope 
1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions.

DisplayName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
AlertName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
Description:
A known credential theft tool execution command line was detected.
Either the process itself or its command line indicated an intent to dump users' credentials, keys, plain-text passwords and more.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

{"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.Category":"CredentialAccess","MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationId":null,"MicrosoftDefenderAtp.InvestigationState":"UnsupportedAlertType","LastUpdated":"06/27/2024 14:37:22","IncidentId":"357","DetectionSource":"WindowsDefenderAtp","AssignedTo":null,"Determination":null,"Classification":null,"Action":"Validate the alert, collect artifacts, and determine scope 
1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"f5d3c5d8-ec3a-4412-ab45-934d8faff42c","MitreTechniques":"T1003","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

DisplayName: PsExec launched a command on a remote device
AlertName: PsExec launched a command on a remote device
Description: PsExec was used to launch a command on a remote device. PsExec is a tool used to launch programs on remote, or local devices. An attacker might be leveraging this tool to launch malicious commands to a remote device and move laterally in the organization.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that is related to the alert. Inspect parent processes and why they were launched.
2. Take note of the name of the remote device and the command that might have been executed.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.​
5. Check the timeline of both the devices for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident.
1. Find related alerts and activities on both devices. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph.
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors.
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites.

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords
4. Block IP addresses and URLs.
5. Install security updates.

D. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. DisplayName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
AlertName: Malicious credential theft tool execution detected
Description:
A known credential theft tool execution command line was detected.
Either the process itself or its command line indicated an intent to dump users' credentials, keys, plain-text passwords and more.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

1. Inspect the file or URL/IP for suspicious characteristics – is it digitally signed? How prevalent is it? Where is it located? Do the domain registration and hosting history look normal?  
2. Review the machine timeline for suspicious activities that may have occurred before and after the time of the alert. 
3. Look for the presence of relevant artifacts on other systems. Identify commonalities and differences between potentially compromised systems. 
4. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review resulting detailed behavioral information. 
5. If alert characteristics and machine behavioral evidence constitute a true positive, consider some of the initial mitigation actions below. Then, contact your incident response team for potential forensic analysis and remediation. 

Initiate containment & mitigation  
1. Record all relevant artifacts to be used in mitigation rules and as new threat intel 
2. Contact the user to check if the observed behavior was intended. 
3. Update AV signatures and run a full scan. The scan might reveal and remove previously-undetected malware components. 
4. Ensure that the machine has the latest security updates. In particular, ensure that you have installed the latest software, web browser, and Operating System versions. 
5. If credential theft is suspected, reset all relevant users passwords. 
6. Disconnect the machine from the network to prevent any threat attack progression. 
7. Block communication with relevant URLs or IPs at the organization’s perimeter.","ThreatName":null,"ThreatFamilyName":null,"DetectorId":"f5d3c5d8-ec3a-4412-ab45-934d8faff42c","MitreTechniques":"T1003","ProcessedBySentinel":"True","Alert generation status":"Full alert created"}

DisplayName: Possible use of the Rubeus kerberoasting tool
AlertName: Possible use of the Rubeus kerberoasting tool
Description:
Activity indicating the use of the Rubeus tool was observed on this endpoint. This tool can perform kerberoasting, pass-the-ticket, and other attack techniques that take advantage of Kerberos authentication.

During these attacks, attackers often request Kerberos tickets for an account's service principal name (SPN). They then decrypt the tickets to get plaintext credentials associated with the account. Alternatively, they can perform the pass-the-ticket technique to authenticate directly without having to decrypt the obtained tickets.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. NOTE: If you don’t have an incident response team, contact Microsoft Support for architectural remediation and forensic.","3. Install and run Microsoft’s Malicious Software Removal Tool (see https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/malicious-software-removal-tool-details.aspx).","4. Run Microsoft’s Autoruns utility and try to identify unknown applications that are configured to run at login (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb963902.aspx).","5. Run Process Explorer and try to identify unknown running processes (see https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspx)."]

Description:
The Mimikatz hacktool was detected on this device. Mimikatz is a credential theft tool that can harvest plaintext passwords, password hashes, smartcard PINs, and Kerberos tickets.  An attacker might be trying to harvest credentials to log into this or other devices on the network, by impersonating a valid user.

For more information, read the Mimikatz tool profile Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/51db19ab-081f-46f3-9fe1-3f5e5d2f8ee0/analystreport? and read the Actor profile: Storm-0875 Threat Analytics report https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/4f60801d-912e-4bcb-91b2-f46879c8a718/analystreport

Description: A Security IDentifcation (SID) history injection was detected on this device. SID history is an attribute that supports migration scenarios. Attackers typically use attack tools to change the SID history of an existing domain user to an SID with elevated privileges. With elevated privileges, the affected process might be able to access sensitive files, ensure persistence, and modify system settings.
RemediationSteps: ["1. Make sure the machine is completely updated and all your software has the latest patch.","2. Contact your incident response team. Validate the alert.
1. Locate the process that is related to the alert. Inspect parent processes and why they were launched.
2. Take note of the command that might have been executed.
3. Verify the unusual system activity with system owners.​
4. Check files for prevalence, their locations, and digital signatures.​
5. Check the timeline of both the devices for other suspicious activities around the time of the alert.
6. Submit relevant files for deep analysis and review file behaviors. ​

B. Scope the incident.
1. Find related alerts and activities within the device. Find out whether they are part of a wider incident in the incident graph.
2. Identify unexpected processes, check suspicious files for prevalence, location and digital signature, submit for deep analysis to inspect behaviors.
3. Identify communications to devices, network addresses, and domains. Verify unusual activities with device owners. Check reputation of URLs and websites. 

C. Contain and mitigate the breach.
1. If activity on any of the involved devices is unexpected, isolate the device to prevent the threat from progressing.
2. Stop suspicious processes.
3. Decommission compromised accounts or reset passwords
4. Block IP addresses and URLs.
5. Install security updates.

Description:
Malware and unwanted software are undesirable applications that perform annoying, disruptive, or harmful actions on affected machines. Some of these undesirable applications can replicate and spread from one machine to another. Others are able to receive commands from remote attackers and perform activities associated with cyber attacks.

A malware is considered active if it is found running on the machine or it already has persistence mechanisms in place. Active malware detections are assigned higher severity ratings.

Because this malware was active, take precautionary measures and check for residual signs of infection.
